<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-meaning-from-bits" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Making Meanings from Bit Representations</title>

  <introduction>
    <p> The central innovation that led to the successful development of the computer was the understanding of binary as a fundamental means of transforming meaning.
      Binary decisions are significantly less expensive and faster than analog/continuous ones, and have proven to be implementable in multiple technologies, from vacuum tubes, to transistors to integrated circuits and even optics.
      The key to this usefulness is the work of the computing machine, both as a binary instruction, and as the data that the instruction aims to manipulate. 
      In both cases, the question is the interpretation of meaning: The meaning of the bits as data, and the meaning of the bits as instructions.
     </p>
<p>
  Binary operations in a computer are built from the understanding of how the mathematics actually work; 
    When using the CPU, there are specific instructions that the <term>machine codes</term> that the computer hardware responds to. 
    This is the purpose of a <term>computer architecture</term>, to support the reading of instructions as machine codes, execute those instructions, and manipulate the data based on those the instructions.

</p>

  </introduction>
  <p>
    Binary bits have no meaning in themselves, their only meaning is the meaning encoded in the hardware to interpret machine codes and to manipulate data. 
    Hence the interpretation of binary bits is central to every understanding of how a computer works.
    While there is a deep and long history to each of these topics, four classic types of bit interpretations: Numbers, specifically Integer Numbers, Floating-Point Numbers, Characters (and hence strings), and Instructions. 
    Each of the following brief chapters introduces a common style of interpreting bits, along with interactive exercises to aid understanding and application.
  </p>

